JSVGComponent.java, line  953 (batik 1.5) reads:

        try {
            inv = renderingTransform.createInverse();
        } catch (NoninvertibleTransformException e) {
            throw new InternalError(e.getMessage());
        }

An InternalException is thrown if the transform is not correct (determinent == 0
for example).

This bug is about coding style, not an error I get while using batik. A method
should never throw an InternalError, but a RuntimeException (or a specialized
subclass of Exception). InternalError (and all other Error) are special
exeptions that are thrown by the VM, not the application.
